From e8c983808d8b98a71f991c16c24367494386958b Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Simon Ser <contact@emersion.fr>
Date: Tue, 14 Jul 2026 20:49:43 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] compositor: reset wlr_surface.buffer when texture creation
 fails

When we fail to import a buffer committed by the client, we leave the
old struct wlr_client_buffer untouched. This causes desynchronization
issues when the buffer size changes. For instance, if the client uses
wp_viewporter, the compositor will attempt to apply the viewport on the
old buffer, which may be out-of-bounds. This can trigger assertions
when attempting to render the buffer.

Instead, reset the buffer field to NULL to signal to the compositor
that a texture could not be created. Leave it up to the compositor
to handle the situation: e.g. disconnect the client, do not render
the surface, or render a placeholder.

Closes: https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/wlroots/wlroots/-/work_items/4079
---
 types/wlr_compositor.c | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/types/wlr_compositor.c b/types/wlr_compositor.c
index 75faed190..50b0ed5fe 100644
--- a/types/wlr_compositor.c
+++ b/types/wlr_compositor.c
@@ -435,7 +435,7 @@ static void surface_apply_damage(struct wlr_surface *surface) {
 
 	if (buffer == NULL) {
 		wlr_log(WLR_ERROR, "Failed to upload buffer");
-		return;
+		// Reset surface's client buffer to NULL to indicate failed upload
 	}
 
 	if (surface->buffer != NULL) {
